'''Beatrix S. Loughran''' (June 30, 1900 in [[New York City]] â December 7, 1975) was an American [[figure skating|figure skater]] who competed in [[single skating]] and [[pair skating]]. She is the only American to win three Olympic medals in figure skating (1924, 1928, 1932). She is a six-time National champion (1925-1927 in singles, 1930-1932 in pairs). Her pairs partner was [[Sherwin Badger]].

She was the aunt of three-time national medalist [[Audrey Peppe]].<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |authorlink= |coauthors= |title= Five Little Pretenders |url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,759202,00.html?promoid=googlep |work= |publisher= [[Time Magazine]] |date= 1938-03-07 |accessdate=2008-06-06 }}</ref>

In 1997, Loughran was inducted into the [[United States Figure Skating Hall of Fame]].

